A TRADABLE INSURANCE-BASED PRODUCT FOR FIRST-CLASS CUSTOMERS

SECTION I: Clients Identification

Load data

We load data from BankClients.mat file: it contains a variety of informations about bank clients.
load('BankClients.mat');
Informations range stretches from usual non-financial people features (age, gender, area, city size) to economically relevant characteristics (job, income, wealth, digital, life style, luxury) to financial attitudes (debt, financial education, ESG*, bank friendliness, saving and investment).
* ESG stands for Environmental, Social, Governance and refers to that financial area linked to responsible investments.

Data Exploration & Transformation

Some of the variables are often extremely correlated, so keeping just one may be more beneficial than having them all.
figure;
gplotmatrix([BankClients.Income BankClients.FinEdu BankClients.BankFriend],[],[],[],[],[],[],...
'grpbars',{'Income','Financial Education','Bank Friendliness'});
title('Multivariate Plot For Potentially Correlated Features I',"Interpreter",'latex');
figure;
gplotmatrix([BankClients.ESG BankClients.Digital],[],[],[],[],[],[],'grpbars',{'ESG','Digital'});
title('Multivariate Plot For Potentially Correlated Features II',"Interpreter",'latex');
From this graph nothing relevant emerges, only Financial Education and Income show a slight positive correlation but it is not enough to exclude one of them from the regressors group.
Let us check Income and Wealth features. Why? They are often distributed with a power law and often need a transformation to be properly suited for machine learning.
figure;
subplot(2,1,1); histogram(BankClients.Income,100);
title('Income',"Interpreter",'latex');
subplot(2,1,2); histogram(BankClients.Wealth,100);
title('Wealth',"Interpreter",'latex');
Here we do not recognise the problem above therefore no transformation is suggested.

Feature Engineering

We realised that the Income voice could be misleading. A simple example: two people have the same income. Do they dispose of this money the same way? Probably yes. But what if the first lives alone and the second has a family with 6 children? The answer to the previous question would likely become a "no". The aim of Adjusted Income is exactly this one: taking into account family size when dealing with income.
AdjIncome = BankClients.Income./log(BankClients.FamilySize+1);

Prepare Data

We are interested only in a particular type of client. He must:
  • Be incline to invest in accumulation products.
  • Have a higher-than-average attitude for saving.
This kind of people will be marked with the label 1. The others will be in tier 0.
As common and useful procedure, regressors are going to be rescaled before their usage.
% create the label
y = double(BankClients.Investments == '3' & BankClients.Saving >= 0.5);
% rescale regressors
X = [rescale(BankClients.Income) rescale(AdjIncome) rescale(BankClients.Wealth)...
rescale(BankClients.Debt) rescale(BankClients.FinEdu) rescale(BankClients.ESG)...
rescale(BankClients.Digital) rescale(BankClients.BankFriend) rescale(BankClients.LifeStyle)...
rescale(BankClients.Luxury)];
% create final matrix with ready-to-use data
Data = [X y];
numberObs = length(Data);
Now we have assigned a label to each client. Of course the two features we used will not be regressors for the supervised machine learning techniques that will follow.
Final preparatory step is to divide properly the dataset, partitioning it into training and test set (the validation set will be generated afterwards inside each machine learning function). We choose to use 15% of initial data for testing purposes.
% for reproducibility
rng('default');
% 15% for test
cv = cvpartition(numberObs,'HoldOut',0.15);
% training set
DataTrain = Data(cv.training,:);
% test set
DataTest = Data(cv.test,:);
% names of regressors and response variable
Datanames= {'Income','Adjusted Income','Wealth','Debt','Financial Education','ESG','Digital',...
'Bank Friendliness','Life Style','Luxury','Client Type'};
% final training set table
TrainTable = table(DataTrain(:,1),DataTrain(:,2),DataTrain(:,3),DataTrain(:,4),...
DataTrain(:,5),DataTrain(:,6),DataTrain(:,7),DataTrain(:,8),DataTrain(:,9),...
DataTrain(:,10),DataTrain(:,11),'VariableNames',Datanames);
% final test set table
TestTable = table(DataTest(:,1),DataTest(:,2),DataTest(:,3),DataTest(:,4),...
DataTest(:,5),DataTest(:,6),DataTest(:,7),DataTest(:,8),DataTest(:,9),...
DataTest(:,10),DataTest(:,11),'VariableNames',Datanames);
Let us check the distribution of the labels: we must be aware in case they are fairly unbalanced.
figure;
subplot(1,2,1); histogram(y(cv.training));
title('Histogram For Training Set Label',"Interpreter",'latex');
subplot(1,2,2); histogram(y(cv.test));
title('Histogram For Test Set Label',"Interpreter",'latex');
In the complete dataset, the label is approximately distributed with a percentage 30%-70%. The same ratio is retained via cvpartition in both subsets.
% clear all the non-needed variables
% clearvars -except TestTable TrainTable

Models Showcase

We can now begin to try different models and assess them. We will not resort to cross-validation: instead the validation procedure will be carried out separately in a held-out part of the training section. Its size is 17.5% of the training set (which is the 85% of the starting data) hence it is roughly 15% of the original one.
OptimisationSettings = struct("Holdout",0.175,...
"ShowPlots",false,...
"Verbose",0,...
"AcquisitionFunctionName",'expected-improvement-plus');
One remark about expected-improvement-plus: we use this specification to be sure that our results will be reproducible.

Classification Tree

The first method we exploit is the Classification Tree. It is a fast and classical method. We thought it would be perfectly suited for a first execution.
rng('default');
Model1 = fitctree(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
"Reproducible",true,...
"OptimizeHyperparameters",'auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings);
y_predicted = predict(Model1,TestTable);
Model_names = {'Single Tree'};
ClassificationStatistics(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted,Model_names,'on');
Method Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score _______________ ________ _________ ______ ________ {'Single Tree'} 0.70133 0 0 0
Results are far from being perfect: the classifier marks everything with the zero label. How can we improve this poor situation? Let us try rebalancing misclassification costs.
We modify misclassification costs by increasing the penalty for false negative misclassification (the worst one for us: we are not reaching out a client that would have probably happily bought our product!). Now this type of mistake counts double.
rng('default')
Model2 = fitctree(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
"Reproducible",true,...
"OptimizeHyperparameters",'auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings,...
"Cost",[0 1;2 0]);
y_predicted = [y_predicted predict(Model2,TestTable)];
Model_names = [Model_names, {'Single Tree (Modified Cost)'}];
ClassificationStatistics(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted,Model_names);
Method Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score _______________________________ ________ _________ _______ ________ {'Single Tree' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'Single Tree (Modified Cost)'} 0.61467 0.40793 0.64286 0.49913
confusionchart(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted(:,end));
From our point of view, results are now significantly better even though the number of false positive can still be subject to improvements.

Random Forest

The natural evolution of the classification tree is the random forest. We perform this technique by selecting trees as learners in the fitcensemble matlab function (which by default has a far more broad range). Learning from the past experience, we directly try also the modified misclassification penalty.
rng('default');
TreeBasis = templateTree('Reproducible',true);
Model3 = fitcensemble(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
"OptimizeHyperparameters",'auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings,...
"Learners",TreeBasis);
rng('default');
Model4 = fitcensemble(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
"OptimizeHyperparameters",'auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings,...
"Learners",TreeBasis,...
"Cost",[0 1;2 0]);
y_predicted = [y_predicted predict(Model3,TestTable) predict(Model4,TestTable)];
Model_names = [Model_names,{'Ensemble','Ensemble (Modified Costs)'}];
ClassificationStatistics(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted,Model_names);
Method Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score _______________________________ ________ _________ ________ ________ {'Single Tree' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'Single Tree (Modified Cost)'} 0.61467 0.40793 0.64286 0.49913 {'Ensemble' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'Ensemble (Modified Costs)' } 0.69067 0.25 0.017857 0.033333
The Ensemble method is not satisfactory even with the modified costs settings.

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

The last approach we are testing is Support Vector Machine. This might be really useful especially because it can be used also in non-linear contexts using the Gaussian Kernel. We are therefore applying three different sets of specifications (which share the automatic optimisation of the parameters):
  1. SVM
  2. SVM with different error weights
  3. SVM with different error weights and Gaussian Kernel
rng('default');
Model5 = fitcsvm(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
'OptimizeHyperparameters','auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings);
rng('default');
Model6 = fitcsvm(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
'OptimizeHyperparameters','auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings,...
"Cost",[0 1;2 0]);
rng('default');
Model7 = fitcsvm(TrainTable,'Client Type',...
'OptimizeHyperparameters','auto',...
"HyperparameterOptimizationOptions",OptimisationSettings,...
"Cost",[0 1;2 0],...
"KernelFunction",'gaussian');
y_predicted = [y_predicted predict(Model5,TestTable)...
predict(Model6,TestTable) predict(Model7,TestTable)];
Model_names = [Model_names,{'SVM','SVM (Modified Costs)',...
'SVM (Modified Costs and Gaussian Kernel)'}];
ClassificationStatistics(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted,Model_names);
Method Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score ____________________________________________ ________ _________ ________ ________ {'Single Tree' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'Single Tree (Modified Cost)' } 0.61467 0.40793 0.64286 0.49913 {'Ensemble' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'Ensemble (Modified Costs)' } 0.69067 0.25 0.017857 0.033333 {'SVM' } 0.70133 0 0 0 {'SVM (Modified Costs)' } 0.60667 0.39009 0.5625 0.46069 {'SVM (Modified Costs and Gaussian Kernel)'} 0.61867 0.41799 0.70536 0.52492
The third usage of SVM seems the winning one. All its statistics are better than the others.
Let us plot the confusion matrix to have a visual check of the outcome.
confusionchart(TestTable{:,end},y_predicted(:,end));
Again the amount of false positives is worrisome but it is the price to pay in order to obtain a low value of false negatives and good performance when identifyfing our target consumers.

SECTION II: Portfolio Replica

Load Data

We load InvestmentReplica.mat file: it contains weekly data from 27/04/1999 to 20/04/2021 of a selection of futures and various indexes regarding hedge funds performances.
load("InvestmentReplica.mat");

Prepare Data: creating the Hedge Fund Pooled Index (HFPI)

We create a supreme index which includes informations from the other indices. It is simply thought as the average of those three values:
  • HFRXGL: HFRX Global Hedge Fund Index
  • MXWO: Invesco MSCI World UCITS ETF Acc
  • LEGATRUU: Bloomberg Barclays Global-Aggregate Total Return Index Value
% build the target hedge fund
% first returns
hedge_returns = 1/3*sum(price2ret([HFRXGL MXWO LEGATRUU]),2);
% then prices (normalised at initial date)
hedge_price = ret2price(hedge_returns);
Let us have a look at what we are going to replicate.
% plot funds levels
figure;
plot(Date,HFRXGL/HFRXGL(1),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);
hold on; grid on;
plot(Date,MXWO/MXWO(1),'Color',[0 0.6 0.4]);
plot(Date,LEGATRUU/LEGATRUU(1),'Color',[0.1 0 0.9]);
plot(Date,hedge_price,'-.k','LineWidth',1);
title('Indeces And Their Mix: HFPI','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('HFRXGL','MXWO','LEGATRUU','Hedge Fund Pooled Index (HFPI)',...
"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
We set up the collection of futures we are going to use to replicate the supreme index. More specifically, these are the Futures we can exploit:
  1. CO1 = Brent (Oil)
  2. DU1 = Schatz (2yrs Gvt Ger)
  3. ES1 = S&P 500 ( US Equity)
  4. GC1 = Gold
  5. LLL1 = MSCI Emerging Markets (EM Equity)
  6. NQ1 = Nasdaq 100 (Tech Equity)
  7. RX1 = Bund (10 Yrs Ger)
  8. TP1 = Topix (Jap. Equity)
  9. TU2 = 2Yrs US Treasury (US Gvt)
  10. TY1 = 10Yrs US Treasury (US Gvt)
  11. VG1 = Eurostoxx 50 (EU Equity)
Futures are extremely liquid products thus fit perfectly this role.
% financial instruments we will use to replicate the index
% first returns
futures_returns = price2ret([CO1 DU1 ES1 GC1 LLL1 NQ1 RX1 TP1 TU2 TY1 VG1]);
% and prices (not normalised)
futures_prices = [CO1 DU1 ES1 GC1 LLL1 NQ1 RX1 TP1 TU2 TY1 VG1];
% plot futures levels
figure; plot(Date,futures_prices./futures_prices(1,:));
grid on;
title('Our Tools: Futures','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
Finally we clear the non-needed variables: preparatory steps are over.
% clearvars -except hedge_returns hedge_price futures_returns futures_prices Date
n_obs_hedgefunds = length(hedge_returns);

Back-Testing Technique

Settings

Before starting with important computations, parameters must be set. First of all the rolling window. The most used one will be y3, which corresponds to 3 years (156 weeks).
% rolling window horizons
y3 = 156; % 3 years
y2 = 104; % 2 years
y1 = 52; % 1 year
We are going to implement VaR restrictions. One key step is deciding how to compute it: our VaR will be parametric and with these two sets of specifications:
  1. Normal distribution, 1 month time horizon, 95% confidence level, 20% limit
  2. T-Student distribution with 2 degree of freedom, 1 month time horizon, 99% confidence level, 15% limit
% VaR settings
VaR_settings_1 = struct('type','n','df',[],'scaling',4,'alpha',0.95,'limit',0.2);
VaR_settings_2 = struct('type','t','df',2,'scaling',4,'alpha',0.99,'limit',0.15);

Regressions showcase

We now proceed to replicate our target index using the provided futures. After a quick glance at the Regression Learner Application we apply three different regression techniques with regularization:
  • Balanced Elastic Net
  • Pure Lasso
  • Ridge
Each regression is implemented inside the Back-Testing loop: we select a time-width which will move forward and for each time we execute the regression on that window data in order to forecast the return of the first week immediately after the current timeframe.
% backtesting with elastic net
[~, returns_bt_en] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3);
% backtesting with lasso
[~, returns_bt_ls] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'off',[],'mid',1);
% backtesting with ridge
[~, returns_bt_rd] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'off',[],'mid',0.01);
We can plot the level of our target and the levels of our replicas.
% plot target level
figure;
plot(Date(y3-1:n_obs_hedgefunds-1),hedge_price(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds)/hedge_price(y3),'-.k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot replicas level
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_en),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_ls),'Color',[0 0.6 0.4]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_rd),'Color',[0.1 0 0.9]);
title('Portfolio Replica: BackTesting With Different Regression Techniques','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('Target Fund','Balanced Elastic Net','Pure Lasso','Ridge',...
"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
First we can see that the replicas behave well and they can track quite effectively the mark. A second thing to notice is that we do not see such a huge difference among these methods, therefore we are probably going to use the technique in the middle of the extremes (i.e. a balanced elastic net).
With statistics regarding the Tracking Error (TE = target returns - replica returns) we can get a quantitative idea about how the methods really performed.
% plot performances statistics
TrackingErrorStatistics(hedge_returns(y3+1:n_obs_hedgefunds),[returns_bt_en,returns_bt_ls,...
returns_bt_rd],{'Balanced Elastic Net';'Pure Lasso';'Ridge'});
Method Average |TE| TE annualised volatilty TE vector L^1 norm ________________________ ____________ _______________________ __________________ {'Balanced Elastic Net'} 0.0026817 0.028107 1.4696 {'Pure Lasso' } 0.0026395 0.027451 1.4464 {'Ridge' } 0.0026852 0.028164 1.4715
Again, there are no huge differences hence no method outperforms the others. The balanced Elastic Net presents a fairly low annualised volatility and a decrease in the mean of the absolute Tracking Error.

Different Rolling Window Sizes

We now want to explore how the rolling window width impacts our regression. Expected results are that smaller sizes lead to a less robust estimate of coefficients so they are more influenced by single events that can be misleading.
% backtesting: 2 years reference
[~, returns_bt_2y] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y2);
% backtesting: 1 year reference
[~, returns_bt_1y] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y1);
Let us plot results and analyse the Tracking Error to get effectively a glimpse of the situation.
% plot target level
figure;
plot(Date(y3-1:n_obs_hedgefunds-1),hedge_price(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds)/hedge_price(y3),'-.k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot replicas level
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_en),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_2y(y1+1:end)),'Color',[0 0.6 0.4]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_1y(y2+1:end)),'Color',[0.1 0 0.9]);
title('Portfolio Replica: Different Rolling Window Sizes','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('Target Fund','3 years','2 years','1 year',...
"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
% plot performances statistics
TrackingErrorStatistics(hedge_returns(y3+1:n_obs_hedgefunds),[returns_bt_en,...
returns_bt_2y(y1+1:end),returns_bt_1y(y2+1:end)],...
{'Elastic Net 3 years';'Elastic Net 2 years';'Elastic Net 1 year'});
Method Average |TE| TE annualised volatilty TE vector L^1 norm _______________________ ____________ _______________________ __________________ {'Elastic Net 3 years'} 0.0026817 0.028107 1.4696 {'Elastic Net 2 years'} 0.0027282 0.02838 1.4951 {'Elastic Net 1 year' } 0.0028197 0.027934 1.5452
Expectations are satisfied: the annualised volatility of the Tracking Error grows as the window shrinks. This may not always be a malevolent effect as it can be exploited during highly volatile periods when adapting quickly may results in greater benefits (or reduced losses).

Limiting Value at Risk (VaR)

We now want to implement a constraint related to VaR level. VaR is an important reference in risk management and its assessment can be required by regulators. Even if not obliged, an investor might still want to know (and perhaps to limit) its value as a precautionary measure against unexpected losses.
We propose two ways to implement a controlled VaR level:
  • "Perfect": the optimisation (of the preferred regularised regression) is performed simultaneously with the VaR constraint via fmincon Matlab function
  • "Fast": the VaR constraint is applied by simply moduling the coefficients obtained via a non-limited regression
We start with the implementation of the first set of VaR constraint: Normal distribution, 1 month time horizon, 95% confidence level, 20% limit.
% backtesting with elastic net and VaR limits I
% optimal procedure
[~, returns_var1] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'perfect',VaR_settings_1);
% fast and (rough) procedure
[~, returns_var1_fast] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'fast',VaR_settings_1);
Let us look at the results. Will VaR limit affect the quality of our mimic portfolio?
% plot target level
figure;
plot(Date(y3-1:n_obs_hedgefunds-1),hedge_price(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds)/hedge_price(y3),'-.k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot replicas levels with VaR contraint I
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_var1),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_var1_fast),'Color',[0 0.6 0.4]);
title('Portfolio Replica: Gaussian VaR Limitation','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('Target Fund','Perfect','Fast',"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
% plot performances statistics
TrackingErrorStatistics(hedge_returns(y3+1:n_obs_hedgefunds),[returns_bt_en,returns_var1,...
returns_var1_fast],...
{'No VaR Limit';'Normal VaR (Perfect)';'Normal VaR (Fast)'});
Method Average |TE| TE annualised volatilty TE vector L^1 norm ________________________ ____________ _______________________ __________________ {'No VaR Limit' } 0.0026817 0.028107 1.4696 {'Normal VaR (Perfect)'} 0.0026705 0.027623 1.4634 {'Normal VaR (Fast)' } 0.0027296 0.029331 1.4958
We did not receive any surprise: the best method is the most rigorous. The remarkable fact is that the VaR constraint, when implemented in the best way, does not seem to compromise (or just to worsen) the regression: it actually even improves some TE statistics.
We now propose a new VaR limit which is harsher than the previous one: T-Student distribution with 2 degrees of freedom, 1 month time horizon, 99% confidence level, 15% limit. It can be for conservative investors, for some particular stress test or, without fantasy, just to test if functions work and to exercise in explaining results.
% backtesting with elastic net and VaR limits II
% optimal procedure
[~, returns_var2] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'perfect',VaR_settings_2);
% fast and (rough) procedure
[~, returns_var2_fast] = BackTesting(futures_returns,hedge_returns,y3,'fast',VaR_settings_2);
Here we would not be astounded if restrictions reshaped results.
% plot target level
figure;
plot(Date(y3-1:n_obs_hedgefunds-1),hedge_price(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds)/hedge_price(y3),'-.k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot replicas levels with VaR contraint II
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_var2),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_var2_fast),'Color',[0 0.6 0.4]);
title('Portfolio Replica: T-Student VaR Limitation','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('Target Fund','Perfect','Fast',"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
% plot performances statistics
TrackingErrorStatistics(hedge_returns(y3+1:n_obs_hedgefunds),[returns_bt_en,returns_var2,...
returns_var2_fast],...
{'No VaR Limit';'T-Student VaR (Perfect)';'T-Student VaR (Fast)'});
Method Average |TE| TE annualised volatilty TE vector L^1 norm ___________________________ ____________ _______________________ __________________ {'No VaR Limit' } 0.0026817 0.028107 1.4696 {'T-Student VaR (Perfect)'} 0.002708 0.027996 1.484 {'T-Student VaR (Fast)' } 0.0027684 0.029277 1.5171
Outcomes are worsened by this new VaR limit, especially for the "Fast" approach which shows some troubles in replicating. Whether or not this difference is relevant must be judged.
Finally we compare the replicas obtained via the two distinct Value at Risk settings.
% plot target level
figure;
plot(Date(y3-1:n_obs_hedgefunds-1),hedge_price(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds)/hedge_price(y3),'-.k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot the level of the replica obtained via Elastic Net (no constraints)
plot(Date(y3:n_obs_hedgefunds),ret2price(returns_bt_en),'Color',[0.7 0 0.3]);

Method Average |TE| TE annualised volatilty TE vector L^1 norm _________________ ____________ _______________________ __________________ {'No VaR Limit' } 0.0026817 0.028107 1.4696 {'Gaussian VaR' } 0.0026705 0.027623 1.4634 {'T-Student VaR'} 0.002708 0.027996 1.484
Plot and statistics show that the two constrained portfolios can replicate the trend and more generally the trajectory of the original index. Overall we would have expected a higher impact of VaR limits on the replica: probably these conditions were too mild or simply they did not affect that much the regression. This may be both a positive and a negative finding, depending upon the opinion about portfolio restrictions: are they a fundamental tool to manage money or just an annoying compliance?

Bootstrap Technique

We abandon momentarily the backtesting method to explore the bootstrap approach to our problem. The main underlying idea is to divide our data into a predefined number of samples and then compute for each one the relative coefficients. The result is the distribution of the coefficients which we are going to exploit to get the average value and a confidence interval.
Let us start using as internal function the balanced elastic net and a 95% probability for the confidence interval.
% confidence level for confidence interval
p = 0.95;
% bootstrap with an internal elastic net
[~,boot_returns_en] = bootstrapFun(futures_returns,hedge_returns,p);
% plot target level
figure;

Mimicking Other Products

We now continue our enquiry regarding portfolios replica. Is it possible to hedge other types of products, for example insurance items with guarantees? Let us imagine a unit linked product with a generous guarantee. Based on the HFPI, this merch proposes at each date a guaranteed value of the 95% of the maximum experienced. Here we do not wonder about whether this product is feasible or not, it is just outside the immediate scope of this project.
% create unit linked product with guarantee
index_maxima = zeros(length(hedge_price),1);
% vector with running maxima
for i = 1:length(hedge_price)
index_maxima(i) = max(hedge_price(1:i));
end
guarantee = max(hedge_price,0.95*index_maxima);
% normalise
guarantee = guarantee/guarantee(1);
guarantee_returns = price2ret(guarantee);
Let us have a quick glimpse about what we are currently managing. Both prices and returns may be interesting.
% plot initial fund level
figure;
plot(Date,hedge_price,'-k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot guaranteed product level
plot(Date,guarantee,'-m');
title('Hedge Fund Pooled Index vs Guaranteed Product: Levels','Interpreter',"latex");
xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Value (normalised at starting date)','Interpreter',"latex");
legend('HFPI','Guaranteed Product',"Interpreter","latex","Location","northwest");
% plot initial fund return
figure;
plot(Date(1:end-1),hedge_returns,'-k');
hold on; grid on;
% plot guaranteed product return
plot(Date(1:end-1),guarantee_returns,'-m');

xlabel('Time','Interpreter',"latex");
ylabel('Returns','Interpreter',"latex");

It will be interesting to see how the regression will handle the period with flat null returns interrupted almost at its half by a non-constant part.
We are going to launch a showcase of methods in order to a posteriori compare them.
% confidence level for confidence interval
p = 0.95;
% bootstrap with an internal elastic net
[~, boot_returns_guar_en] = bootstrapFun(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,p);
% bootstrap with an internal lasso
[~, boot_returns_guar_ls] = bootstrapFun(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,p,1e+3,'mid',1);
% backtesting with elastic net: rolling window 1 year
[~, returns_guar_en1y] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y1);
% backtesting with elastic net: rolling window 3 years
[~, returns_guar_en3y] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y3);
% backtesting with lasso: rolling window 3 years
[~, returns_guar_ls] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y3,'off',[],'mid',1);
% backtesting with ridge: rolling window 2 years
[~, returns_guar_rd] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y2,'off',[],'mid',0.2);
% backtesting with elastic net and Normal VaR Limit: rolling window 3 years
[~, returns_guar_var1_en] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y3,'perfect',VaR_settings_1);
% backtesting with lasso and T-Student VaR Limit: rolling window 3 years
[~, returns_guar_var2_ls] = BackTesting(futures_returns,guarantee_returns,y3,...
'perfect',VaR_settings_2,'mid',1);

The statistics had already pointed out a worsening of our techniques tracking ability and the graph remarks this fact even more. The problem lies likely here: we are currently using linear approaches to track something which now is highly non-linear. The trajectory appears indeed too complex to be followed by linear methods.
